      Collateralized fund obligation
   =20
 =20

The  basic move in finance is:
=09You have some cash flows.=09You put them all into a box.=09You slice the=
 box into junior and senior claims.=09You sell the senior claims to people =
who want safe cash flows, and the junior claims to people who want exciting=
 leveraged risk.

Everything is like this: Every company does some business that brings in so=
me cash, and the cash goes first to pay off the company=E2=80=99s debt (its=
 senior claims), and if there=E2=80=99s cash left over it goes to the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s shareholders (the junior claimants). Lending money to the comp=
any is safer than buying its stock, because you get paid back first, but bu=
ying the stock has more upside.
But you can do this with lots of other cash flows, and it has come to be kn=
own as =E2=80=9Csecuritization.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Most famously, you have a bun=
ch of subprime mortgage bonds, you put them into a collateralized debt obli=
gation, you slice it into junior and senior tranches, you get the most seni=
or tranches rated AAA and sell them to banks seeking safety, you leave the =
most junior tranches unrated and give them to people who want a lot of mort=
gage risk. This became the template for this sort of thing, so =E2=80=9Ccol=
lateralized ____ obligation=E2=80=9D became the standard term:=C2=A0collate=
ralized debt obligation (CDO) for mortgages, collateralized loan obligation=
 (CLO) for corporate loans, etc. In 2008, CDOs caused problems, and the mar=
ket for subprime mortgage CDOs still hasn=E2=80=99t recovered. But there ar=
e still lots of other cash-flow-slicing businesses, many of them using the =
C_O terminology, and you can still occasionally read articles about how =E2=
=80=9Cthe same technology that caused the 2008 mortgage crisis is coming fo=
r=E2=80=9D some other business.
Much of this involves taking medium-safe cash flows and parceling them into=
 very safe and pleasingly risky cash flows. A subprime mortgage will probab=
ly get paid back, but the appetite for probably-get-paid-back mortgage risk=
 seems to be less than the combined appetite for (1) very very safe senior =
mortgage risk plus (2) riskier but higher-yielding mortgage risk. Same with=
 leveraged corporate loans or fast-food franchises or whatever. But you can=
 do it with very risky stuff, if you want. We  previously talked about this=
 basic move =E2=80=94=C2=A0put stuff in a box, issue junior and senior clai=
ms =E2=80=94=C2=A0as a way to create decentralized=C2=A0stablecoins in cryp=
to. You put $2 worth of risky cryptocurrency=C2=A0in a box, you issue a $1 =
senior claim on the box and call it a =E2=80=9Cstablecoin=E2=80=9D that is =
always worth a dollar, and you give someone else a $1 levered risky crypto =
bet. If the $2 worth of cryptocurrency rises to $5, the levered junior clai=
mant does well; if it falls to $1, the levered junior claim is wiped out bu=
t the stablecoin is still worth $1. If the $2 worth of cryptocurrency falls=
 to $0.0001,  as happens, then the stablecoin is no longer stable, oops.
Every few years I read someone  proposing to do this with stocks. Like, put=
 the S&P 500 Index in a box, issue senior claims that pay interest and are =
pretty safe, issue junior claims that are a levered bet on stocks, I don=E2=
=80=99t know, like a securitized index margin loan. Fine.=C2=A0
Anyway here=E2=80=99s the Financial Times on collateralized fund obligation=
s:

The product is known as a =E2=80=9Ccollateralised fund obligation=E2=80=9D =
and its aim is to diversify risk by parceling up the companies providing re=
turns. CFOs are, in some ways, a private equity variant of =E2=80=9Ccollate=
ralised debt obligations=E2=80=9D, the bundles of mortgage-backed securitie=
s that only reached the public consciousness when they wreaked havoc during=
 the 2008 financial crisis.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
The vehicle exposed to Envision is one of several CFOs launched by Azalea, =
an independently-run unit of the Singapore state-owned investor Temasek. It=
 is more transparent than most because it is offered to retail investors, t=
hough Azalea does not tell those investors which portfolio companies they a=
re exposed to, citing =E2=80=9Cconfidentiality obligations=E2=80=9D.
In effect, the CFO is a box containing stakes in 38 private equity and grow=
th funds that Azalea committed money to. The funds are managed by many of t=
he industry=E2=80=99s biggest names including Blackstone, KKR, Carlyle and =
General Atlantic. ...
The CFO issues senior and junior bonds, which can be bought by retail inves=
tors and which offer fixed interest payments of 4.1 per cent and 6 per cent=
. When the 38 funds hand cash to their investors, the CFO uses it to make i=
nterest payments, then holds some back in a reserve account designed to ult=
imately pay off the principal.
Any remaining cash, after debt repayments and expenses, goes to the holders=
 of the CFO=E2=80=99s equity, in this case Azalea itself. Owning the equity=
 is =E2=80=9Cnothing more than a levered investment into private equity=E2=
=80=9D, says Jeff Johnston, chairman of the Fund Finance Association.
S&P Global and Fitch rate the senior bonds in Azalea=E2=80=99s CFO as A+, a=
n investment-grade rating that means it is deemed unlikely to default, and =
is far higher than the typical junk-grade ratings of individual private equ=
ity-owned companies.
Azalea told the FT that it structured transactions with =E2=80=9Cdownside r=
isk mitigation in mind=E2=80=9D, using =E2=80=9Cconservative=E2=80=9D loan-=
to-value ratios and putting =E2=80=9Cvarious structural safeguards=E2=80=9D=
 in place to protect investors.

Yeah look if your private equity investments return 15% per year and you ca=
n lever them up by borrowing long-term from retail at 4% per year then that=
